======================================================================
APPROACH 6: Self-correcting formula
======================================================================

Key insight: R^{-1}(n) gives us x0 ≈ p(n) with error ε ≈ sqrt(x0)*ln(x0)/something.
The error ε is SIGNED and its distribution might be predictable.

What if we can compute the EXPECTED SIGN of the error?
Then we know whether to look above or below x0 for p(n).

Even better: what if we can compute the expected error MORE precisely
using information about n itself (its factorization, residues, etc.)?

