    {"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"0d330919-a8e5-4f46-8c87-22d9293c984b","agentId":"af781243c2d61b5a6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"You are working on a research project to find the nth prime number WITHOUT any brute-forcing. The project is at /apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/.\n\nPrevious work (3 sessions, 40+ approaches) concluded that p(10^100) in 1 second is impossible. But we're looking for a breakthrough.\n\nYOUR TASK: Explore LATTICE POINT and GEOMETRIC approaches to prime counting.\n\nKey ideas to investigate:\n1. **Hyperbola method for Euler products**: The prime counting function relates to the Euler product of zeta. Can we express π(x) as a lattice point count in some transformed space?\n\n2. **Perron's formula optimization**: π(x) = (1/2πi) ∫ (log ζ(s)/s) x^s ds. Can we choose a contour that avoids the need for many zeta zeros?\n\n3. **Weil's explicit formula as geometry**: The explicit formula can be viewed as a trace formula on a space. Can we compute this trace more efficiently?\n\n4. **Arithmetic geometry**: Primes correspond to closed geodesics on certain manifolds. Can we count them using geometric methods?\n\n5. **Direct number-theoretic approach**: Instead of going through π(x), can we characterize p(n) directly using properties like:\n   - p(n) is the unique integer m such that ω(m#) = n (where m# is primorial-like)\n   - p(n) relates to the Möbius function in specific ways\n\nWrite a Python script at /apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/session4_experiments/lattice_geometric.py that implements the most promising of these ideas. Use mpmath for precision.\n\nFocus on whether ANY of these reformulations leads to an algorithm faster than O(x^{2/3}) for computing π(x) or p(n) directly. Write working code and report findings."},"uuid":"2bbb3749-127d-4d53-987e-d6e4443d0c56","timestamp":"2026-04-04T04:44:29.458Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"005383