    {"parentUuid":"d05492e8-0714-435f-a298-258da8dd5ef2","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"0d330919-a8e5-4f46-8c87-22d9293c984b","agentId":"a7bc970e2fde4fc3a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XgqhPV7utnUJuDGau1oDmw","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Cloitre analytic recurrence primes arXiv 2508.02690\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"An effective analytic recurrence for prime numbers Benoit Cloitre\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.02690\"},{\"title\":\"[2508.02690] An effective analytic recurrence for prime numbers\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.02690\"},{\"title\":\"An effective analytic recurrence for prime numbers\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02690\"},{\"title\":\"An effective analytic recurrence for prime numbers: from asymptotics to explicit bounds\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02690v1\"},{\"title\":\"Double Recurrence and Almost Sure Convergence: Primes and Weighted Theory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.22203\"},{\"title\":\"A bibliographic view on recurrence plots and recurrence quantification analyses\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.20152\"},{\"title\":\"[math/0412079] Primes Generated by Recurrence Sequences\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0412079\"},{\"title\":\"Primes Generated by Recurrence Sequences\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/math/0412079\"},{\"title\":\"Recurrence Sequences\",\"url\":\"https://www.ams.org/books/surv/104/surv104-endmatter.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"[2508.20152] A bibliographic view on recurrence plots and recurrence quantification analyses\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.20152\"}]\n\nI found the paper! Here's information about arXiv paper 2508.02690:\n\n**Title:** An effective analytic recurrence for prime numbers\n\n**Author:** Benoit Cloitre\n\n**Summary:**\n\nThe Golomb--Keller formula expresses the next prime p_{n+1} as a recurrence relation in terms of the first n primes using the Riemann zeta function and an Euler product, but requires taking a limit as s → ∞, rendering it non-constructive.\n\nCloitre transforms this asymptotic formula into an effective recurrence by proving that a finite parameter s ≤ p_n suffices when combined with the ceiling function, establishing a constructive method valid for all n ≥ 1.\n\n**Key Results:**\n\n- The minimal integer parameter s_n (OEIS A389650) reveals deep connections to prime constellations.\n\n- The paper proves liminf_{n→∞} σ_n = 0 unconditionally, where σ_n = s_n/p_n. The limit superior C = limsup σ_n satisfies log ψ ≲ C ≤ 0.4332, where ψ ≈ 1.46557 is the supergolden ratio. The lower bound is conditional on the twin prime conjecture; the upper bound is unconditional.\n\n**Submission Information:** The paper was submitted on 23 Jul 2025 (v1), with the last revision on 12 Oct 2025 (this version, v2)\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"6fa2a940-1230-45c0-a4fa-88d8f0dfb425","timestamp":"2026-04-04T04:45:17.942Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"d05492e8-0714-435f-a298-258da8dd5ef2","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"00538385-e056-4e78-8f42-1ce75c0130f0","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"purrfect-gliding-lagoon"}
    {"parentUuid":"f25816f1-eae9-49bb-9c68-e676059bc5dc","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"0d330919-a8e5-4f46-8c87-22d9293c984b","agentId":"a7bc970e2fde4fc3a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GUgh69VF3C2LgqEvrcH9aY","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"closed-form formula nth prime number recurrence avoiding prime counting function 2025 2026\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Prime Formulas -- from Wolfram MathWorld\",\"url\":\"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PrimeFormulas.html\"},{\"title\":\"Counting primes in $$$\\\\tilde{{\\\\cal O}}(n^{2/3}\\\\,\\\\,)$$$ - Codeforces\",\"url\":\"https://codeforces.com/blog/entry/91632\"},{\"title\":\"Formula for primes - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formula_for_primes\"},{\"title\":\"An Exact Formula for the Prime Counting Function Jose Risomar Sousa\",\"url\":\"https://empslocal.ex.ac.uk/people/staff/mrwatkin/zeta/sousa_2020_sigma.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Formulas for the n-th prime number\",\"url\":\"https://nntdm.net/papers/nntdm-27/NNTDM-27-4-129-139.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Prime-counting function - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime-counting_function\"},{\"title\":\"Prime Counting Function -- from Wolfram MathWorld\",\"url\":\"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PrimeCountingFunction.html\"},{\"title\":\"FAQ: Is there a formula for the nth Prime?\",\"url\":\"https://t5k.org/notes/faq/p_n.html\"},{\"title\":\"Is there a formula such that if you were to plug in a value n, the result would be the nth prime number?\",\"url\":\"https://www.quora.com/Is-there-a-formula-such-that-if-you-were-to-plug-in-a-value-n-the-result-would-be-the-nth-prime-number\"},{\"title\":\"Formula for primes — Grokipedia\",\"url\":\"https://grokipedia.com/page/Formula_for_primes\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about closed-form formulas for the nth prime number:\n\n## Current State of Research\n\nThere is no simple closed-form elementary formula that outputs the nth prime using only basic arithmetic and a finite number of standard functions; however, there are many exact formulas and algorithmic constructions that produce the nth prime.\n\n## Key Approaches\n\n**Recurrence Relations:**\nIn 1971 J. M. Gandhi introduced a recurrent formula where μ is the Möbius function. Additionally, there are recurrence relationships that use a constant from which the prime number sequence can be recovered.\n\n**Prime Counting Function-Based Methods:**\nWhile some approaches do use the prime counting function π(n), formulas derived from the prime number theorem involve the inverse of the prime counting function. Willans formula can be used with new forms of π(n) to calculate the nth prime.\n\n**Theoretical Results:**\nA single 26-variable polynomial with integer coefficients has the property that the set of positive values equals the set of prime numbers, and from this one can extract a formula for the nth prime, though this is an existence and exact construction but utterly impractical.\n\n## Limitations\n\nRecurrence relation formulas for primes involve sequences defined by recursive rules that aim to produce prime numbers by building each term iteratively from previous ones, but no such relation is known to generate all primes or exclusively primes infinitely often.\n\nThe search results don't contain recent 2025-2026 publications specifically about avoiding prime counting functions in closed-form formulas.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"b4483b19-6228-4381-8850-1f91563f07bb","timestamp":"2026-04-04T04:45:18.706Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f25816f1-eae9-49bb-9c68-e676059bc5dc","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"00538385-e056-4e78-8f42-1ce75c0130f0","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"purrfect-gliding-lagoon"}
